asList() method is used to convert an array into a list.

fill() method is used to fill a collection with a specified value.

Explanation
new int[5] creates an integer array of size 5.
Arrays.fill(arr, -1) assigns -1 to every index of the array.
The enhanced for loop prints each element followed by a space.

The correct syntax for filling an entire array with a value is Arrays.fill(arr, 5) where arr is the target array and 5 is the value to fill it with.

The mismatch() method in the Arrays class is used to find and return the index of the first differing element between two arrays.

The Arrays.equals() method uses the specified comparator (String::compareToIgnoreCase) for comparison. Since the comparator ignores case differences, the arrays a and b are considered equal, and the output will be Yes.

Arrays.binarySearch(arr, 1, 3, 10) searches for 10 only in the range index 1 (inclusive) to 3 (exclusive) → elements {20, 30}.

Since 10 is not in this range, it returns a negative value indicating the insertion point.

equals() method is used to check if two arrays are equal or not.

Arrays.equals() compares elements index by index. At index 2, a[2] is null and b[2] is 30, so the arrays are not equal.

Arrays.equals(a, 0, 1, b, 0, 1) compares elements from index 0 (inclusive) to 1 (exclusive) in both arrays. Only the first element (10) is compared, and since they are equal, the result is true.
